can Party]]\n| religion = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n| occupation = Businessman, Politician\n| website = [http://chriscollins.house.gov/ chriscollins.house.gov]\n}}\n\n'''Christopher Carl \"Chris\" Collins''' (born May 20, 1950) is an [[United States|American]] politician and member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[New York's 27th congressional district]] since 2013. Previously, he was the [[County Executive]] of [[Erie County, New York]] from 2007 to 2011. He is a resident of [[Clarence, New York]].<ref name=votesmart>{{cite web |title=Representative Chris Collins's Biography |url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/139770/chris-collins#.UNx4jHf4Igo |work=Vote Smart |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and business career==\nBorn in [[Schenectady, New York]], in 1950, Collins moved around the country with his family as his father was transferred several times by [[General Electric]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/democratandchronicle/obituary.aspx?n=gerald-e-collins&pid=138346552#fbLoggedOut |title=Gerald E. Jerry Collins Obituary: View Gerald Collins's Obituary by Rochester Democrat And Chronicle |publisher=Legacy.com |date=2010-01-08 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Collins graduated from [[Hendersonville High School (North Carolina)|Hendersonville High School]] in [[Hendersonville, North Carolina]], in 1968<ref>{{cite web|last=Axtell |first=Nathaniel |url=http://www.blueridgenow.com/article/20121113/ARTICLES/121119929 |title=Congressman-elect Chris Collins of New York is a 1968 graduate of Hendersonville High School |publisher=BlueRidgeNow.com |date=2012-11-13 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> and was inducted into the Hendersonville High School Hall of Fame in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Bill|title=HHS inducts four to Hall of Fame|url=http://www.hendersonvillelightning.com/news/2118-hhs-inducts-four-to-hall-of-fame.html|accessdate=15 October 2013|newspaper=The Hendersonville Lightning|date=11 October 2013}}</ref> He received a BSME from [[North Carolina State University]] in 1972 and an MBA from the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] in 1975.<ref name=votesmart/>\n\nCollins spent thirty-five years in the business world.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} As an entrepreneur he was the founder, President and CEO of Nuttall Gear Corporation located in [[Niagara Falls, New York]].<ref name=votesmart/> Nuttall Gear was a 1983 leveraged buyout of the [[Westinghouse Electric]] Gear Division located in Buffalo, New York.<ref name=\"nuttallgear1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nuttallgear.com/nuttall-history.asp |title=History |publisher=Nuttall Gear |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Collins sold Nuttall in 1997 to a large industrial conglomerate.<ref name=\"nuttallgear1\"/>\n\nAfter losing a race for Congress in 1998, Collins purchased or invested in over twenty bankrupt and financially troubled companies. These companies were combined into several platform companies. His current companies include: Bloch Industries, Easom Automation, Innate Immunotherapeutics, Mead Supply, Oxygen Generating Systems Intl., Schlyer Machine, Volland Electric and ZeptoMetrix Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070923/CITYANDREGION/309239978 |title=Private sector savvy Can Chris Collins' business expertise save Erie County? - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=2007-09-23 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\n\n===1998 congressional election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections, 1998}}\nU.S. Congressman [[Bill Paxon]] (R-NY) convinced Collins to get into politics and challenge 24-year incumbent Democrat U.S. Congressman [[John J. LaFalce]] in [[New York's 29th congressional district]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} During the campaign, Collins was one of the first congressional candidates to call for President [[Bill Clinton]]'s resignation in the wake of the [[Monica Lewinsky scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9B384F4CD4E4&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=News Archives: The Buffalo News |publisher=Nl.newsbank.com |date=1998-10-29 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> LaFalce touted his own record of bringing [[Earmark (politics)|home the bacon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF9B38D85DAEE6&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=News Archives: The Buffalo News |publisher=Nl.newsbank.com |date=1998-10-30 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> and he was re-elected by 58% to 41%.\n\n===Erie County Executive===\n\n====Elections====\nCollins ran for Erie County Executive in 2007 on the platform of smaller county government, lower taxes and [[Six Sigma]].<ref name=polarbear/> His campaign slogan was \"Elect a Chief Executive, not a Chief Politician.\" Collins defeated Democrat James P. Keane, the Deputy County Executive of the [[Dennis Gorski]] administration, with 63% in what was considered an \"upset\" win.<ref name=defeated/>\n\nOn November 8, 2011, Collins lost his bid for re-election, a race he was predicted to win.<ref name=considering/> He was defeated by Democratic candidate [[Mark Poloncarz]], the Erie County Comptroller.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poloncarz Wins Erie County Executive Race |first=Athan |last=Kompos |url=http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/141103/37/Collins-Conceeds-to-Poloncarz-in-Erie-County-Executive-Race |work=[[WGRZ]] |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref> In a county with 140,000 more Democrats than Republicans, Collins won 39 of the 44 municipalities. Poloncarz won the 5 remaining municipalities, most importantly the City of [[Buffalo, NY|Buffalo]], by a margin of 81% to 19%.<ref name=considering>{{cite news |title=Chris Collins Considering Getting Back Into Politics |first=Dave |last=McKinley |url=http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/149180/37/Collins-Considering-Getting-Back-Into-Politics |work=[[WGRZ]] |date=9 January 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Tenure====\nWhen Collins became the County Executive, he inherited from his Republican predecessor, Joel Giambra, a nearly bankrupt county that had state-imposed fiscal control with a budget of $1.2 billion.<ref name=polarbear/><ref name=defeated/>\n\nCollins spoke for 3 minutes at the [[2008 Republican National Convention]] on September 3, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080904/CITYANDREGION/309049954 |title=Collins uses 3 minutes in spotlight to cover a lot of political ground - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=2008-09-04 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> He was the only County Executive in the country given the opportunity to speak at the RNC.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nCollins reduced overall county debt by over $120 million and created a cash surplus in excess of $100 million.<ref>[http://www.erie.gov/exec/pdfs/2012%20EC%20Message.pdf Pg. 25]</ref> He reduced county employment by over 1,200 employees (22%)<ref>[http://www.erie.gov/exec/pdfs/2012%20EC%20Message.pdf Pg. .V]</ref> and fully paid Erie County\u2019s state imposed pension costs without borrowing.<ref>[http://www.erie.gov/exec/pdfs/2012%20EC%20Message.pdf Pg. .IV & .V]</ref> Collins reverted the state imposed Fiscal Control Authority to advisory status in 18 months <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090603/CITYANDREGION/306039994 |title=Control board shifts to advisory status while warning that it 'will not go away' - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=2009-06-03 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> and received approval of a Four Year Financial Plan (2012-2015) that further reduced county debt by another $100 million.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">http://www.erie.gov/exec/pdfs/2012%20EC%20Message.pdf</ref>\n\nCollins reopened every bridge, road, park and beach that had been closed under previous administration, including rebuilding the historic toboggan runs in Chestnut Ridge Park in Orchard Park.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100110/CITYANDREGION/301109985 |title=Tallyho as tobogganers chase thrill Fun seekers pack Chestnut Ridge Park on Saturday as toboggan chutes open - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=2010-01-10 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nAs Erie County Executive, Collins recruited a Six Sigma Master Black Belt from the University at Buffalo who had previously worked as an executive at a Delphi to implement Lean Six Sigma across all county departments under the direction of the County Executive to improve efficiency and reduce costs. The position\u2019s $115,000 salary plus associated costs was funded by a grant of tax-payer money from the Erie County Control Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2007/12/17/daily49.html |title=New, old faces form Collins' team - Buffalo - Business First |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=2007-12-21 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nHe laid off almost 1,000 workers<ref name=polarbear/> and effectively repealed the county\u2019s Apprenticeship Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2009/02/02/daily44.html |title=Collins has plan to lift Erie County - Buffalo - Business First |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=2009-02-05 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nCollins sued the county so that he could unilaterally increase the county attorney's salary by more that $50,000 than the amount authorized by the County Legislature.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spina|first=Matthew|title=Judge orders higher pay for county lawyer|url=http://www2.erie.gov/comptroller/sites/www2.erie.gov.comptroller/files/uploads/pdfs/4-5-11%20Buffalo%20News%20Judge%20orders%20higher%20pay%20for%20county%20lawyer.pdf|accessdate=19 March 2013|newspaper=The Buffalo News|date=April 5, 2011}}</ref> The State Supreme Court Judge presiding over the case ruled in favor of Collins and awarded the higher salary to the incoming County Attorney.<ref>http://www2.erie.gov/comptroller/sites/www2.erie.gov.comptroller/files/uploads/pdfs/4-5-11%20Buffalo%20News%20Judge%20orders%20higher%20pay%20for%20county%20lawyer.pdf</ref>\n\nCollins was sued by the [[United States Department of Justice]] for repeated civil rights violations of prisoners held in county facilities, including juveniles and prisoners with developmental disabilities.<ref>{{cite web|last=United States Department of Justice|title=Justice Department Files Lawsuit Challenging Conditions at Two Erie County, New York, Correctional Facilities|url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/2009/September/09-crt-1053.html|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref> The Department of Justice and Erie County co-signed a stipulated settlement of dismissal in August 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20110818/CITYANDREGION/308189916 |title=U.S. suit on county jail, prison to be dismissed; Justice Department, county attorney sign agreement to end legal action, Collins says - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=2011-08-18 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nHe was also sued by the County Legislature for refusing to issue payments to Erie Community College which had been included in the County's budget.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sampson|first=Doug|title=Erie County Legislature sues County Executive Chris Collins|url=http://buffalo.ynn.com/content/top_stories/523335/erie-county-legislature-sues-county-executive-chris-collins/|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs County Executive, Collins created the Brighter Future Fund, donating his county salary to local non-profit organizations for the first 18 months of his tenure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2008/02/04/daily32.html |title=Top county salaries create 'Bright Future' - Buffalo - Business First |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=2008-02-06 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, Erie County experienced a potential [[Hepatitis A]] emergency when an infected employee handled produce at a popular supermarket.<ref name=\"buffalonews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080215/CITYANDREGION/302159967 |title=Hepatitis scare raises concerns Offers glimpse into nightmare of a flu pandemic - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=2008-02-15 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Over the course of several days, the County vaccinated and inoculated 10,000 people to protect the public. The event was one of the largest vaccination events in the history of the United States.<ref name=\"buffalonews1\"/>\n\nOne year later, tragedy struck Erie County when Continental Flight 3407 crashed in a residential neighborhood, killing all 49 passengers on board, one person on the ground in Clarence Center. Collins declared a State of Emergency. Throughout the night and over the next several days, Collins worked to ensure the cooperation of Erie County departments and other government agencies in the recovery, investigation and family support efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/stories/2009/02/23/story7.html |title=Collins reacted 'on instinct' to crash - Buffalo - Business First |publisher=Bizjournals.com |date=2009-02-23 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2009, southern Erie County \u2013 especially the Village of Gowanda \u2013 was devastated by flooding. Dozens of homeowners lost the contents of their basements and first floors. Collins mobilized the County\u2019s Emergency Services and Public Works departments to assist local governments in their recovery efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090811/CITYANDREGION/308119996 |title=CREEK GOES ON RAMPAGE Torrential rains cause Cattaraugus Creek to flood, leaving 2 dead, roads awash, Gowanda inundated - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date=2009-08-11 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Erie County also successfully lobbied the Federal government to provide FEMA aid dollars to both local governments and individual homeowners.{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nDuring his [[Lame duck (politics)|lame duck]] period as Chief Executive, Collins proposed spending $6m to upgrade housing for polar bears at [[Buffalo Zoo]] at the same time as laying off 155 workers.<ref name=polarbear>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/16/chris-collins-erie-county-polar-bear-housing-layoffs_n_1097326.html |title=Chris Collins, Erie County Executive, Proposes Polar Bear Housing Amid Layoffs |first=John |last=Celock |work=The Huffington Post |date= 16 November 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Political future====\nBeginning in 2009, Collins was mentioned as a potential candidate for [[Governor of New York]] in the [[New York gubernatorial election, 2010|2010 election]], particularly if [[Rudy Giuliani]] decided not to run.<ref>Dicker, Fred (2009-05-18). [http://www.nypost.com/seven/05182009/news/columnists/bizman_pol_is_gopers_plan_b_169868.htm BIZMAN POL IS GOPERS' PLAN B]. New York Post. Retrieved 2009-05-19.</ref><ref name=\"jv0529\">Vielkind, Jimmy (2009-05-29). [http://www.politickerny.com/3787/collins-lazio-up-front-conservative-party-dinner Collins, Lazio Get to Sit Up Front at Conservative Party Dinner].</ref><ref name=\"wben1009\">[http://www.wben.com/Is-Chris-Collins-Running-For-Governor-/5374941 Is Chris Collins running for governor?] [[WBEN (AM)|WBEN]] (2009-10-04). Retrieved 2009-10-07.</ref> Collins had indicated he would make his decision in January 2010, but observers believed he was strongly leaning toward running.<ref name=\"wgrz121709\">Saykin, Aaron (2009-12-17). [http://www.wgrz.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=72883&catid=37 Chris Collins Slams Rick Lazio As He Readies For NY Governor's Race]. [[WGRZ]]. Retrieved 2009-12-17.</ref> After further pondering, Collins decided not to run on January 26, 2010. He cited a desire to focus on his current job and a lack of fundraising support from downstate donors, which he dubbed the \"status quo.\" He did not endorse [[Rick Lazio]] and encouraged the state party to find someone else, either from the business field or possibly cross-endorsing Democrat [[Steve Levy (politician)|Steve Levy]].<ref name=ends>McCarthy, Robert (2010-01-26). [http://www.buffalonews.com/home/story/936045.html Collins ends run for governor]. ''[[The Buffalo News]]''. Retrieved 2010-01-25.</ref>\n\nBefore his re-election defeat, Collins was mentioned as a potential candidate in the [[New York gubernatorial election, 2014|2014 gubernatorial election]].<ref name=defeated>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/09/chris-collins-andrew-cuomo-erie-county_n_1084960.html |title=Chris Collins, Potential Andrew Cuomo Opponent, Defeated In Reelection Bid |first=John |last=Celock |work=The Huffington Post |date= 9 November 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref> After his election to Congress, Collins was again mentioned as a possible gubernatorial candidate. In January 2013, he said that he had \"no intention or interest in running for governor in 2014\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://capitaltonightny.ynn.com/2013/01/collins-run-for-governor-is-off-the-table/ | work=Capital Tonight | first=Nick | last=Reisman | title=\u2018Collins: Run For Governor Is \u2018Off The Table\u2019 | date=27 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2012#District 27}}\nAfter losing his County Executive re-election campaign, Collins ruled out a future bid for office. In January 2012, he was reported to be considering running for Congress<ref name=considering/> and on March 25, 2012, Collins announced he was running in New York's newly-drawn [[New York's 27th congressional district|27th Congressional District]]. The district had previously been the 26th District, and had long been a Republican bastion.  However, in a 2011 special election, Democratic Erie County Clerk [[Kathy Hochul]] became the first Democrat to represent the district in over 40 years.  \n\nOn June 26, 2012 Collins won the Republican primary, defeating [[Iraq War]] veteran [[David Bellavia]] 60%-40%. Collins had the Republican and Conservative party lines for the November general election and defeated Hochul 51%-49%,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2012/house/ny/new_york_27th_district_collins_vs_hochul-3347.html |title=Election 2012 - New York 27th District - Collins vs. Hochul |publisher=RealClearPolitics |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> a difference of 4,312 votes. \n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in New York, 2014#District 27}}\nCollins won re-election to a second term by defeating Democratic opponent Jim O'Donnell 72%-28%.<ref>http://www.cnn.com/election/2014/results/state/NY/house/27</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nCollins was sworn-in on January 3, 2013. Prior to taking the oath of office, House Republican leadership appointed him to serve on both the Agriculture and Small Business committees in the 113th Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbta1490.com/LocalNews/tabid/115/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/3048/Congressman-elect-Chris-Collins-Receives-Committee-Assignments.aspx |title=Congressman-elect Chris Collins Receives Committee Assignments > WBTA AM 1490 Batavia, New York |publisher=Wbta1490.com |date=2012-12-14 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Soon after taking office, House Small Business Committee Chairman [[Sam Graves]] tapped Collins to chair the subcommittee on Healthcare and Technology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130107/CITYANDREGION/130109436 |title=Collins gains rare rookie honor as subcommittee chief - City & Region |publisher=The Buffalo News |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2014 Collins chaired a field hearing, titled ''Expanding Broadband Access and Capabilities to Small Businesses in Rural New York''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Krencik|first=Jim|title=Telecom reps offer testimony at rural broadband hearing|url=http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_4c6ab52e-b0ac-11e3-baa4-001a4bcf887a.html|accessdate=31 March 2014|newspaper=The Daily News|date=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Balaban|first=Howard|title=Collins hears broadband testimony|url=http://www.lockportjournal.com/local/x1387878660/Collins-hears-broadband-testimony|accessdate=31 March 2014|newspaper=Lockport Union - Sun & Journal|date=21 March 2014}}</ref> This field hearing was held at the Orleans County Legislature in Albion, NY, examining access to broadband in rural communities, and the role of the federal government in expanding these capabilities to small businesses.<ref>{{cite news|title=Collins arranges local hearing on broadband issues|url=http://www.journal-register.com/local/x1387869384/Collins-arranges-local-hearing-on-broadband-issues|accessdate=31 March 2014|newspaper=The Medina Journal Register|date=17 March 2014}}</ref> Following the field hearing, Collins hosted a roundtable discussion with local community leaders to continue the discussion on the importance of access to broadband in rural communities. <ref>{{cite news|last=Krencik|first=Jim|title=Life in the \u2018last mile\u2019 is ... (buffering)|url=http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_fdbeed9e-b0a8-11e3-9a85-001a4bcf887a.html|accessdate=31 March 2014|newspaper=The Daily News|date=21 March 2014}}</ref> \n\nIn announcing his committee assignments, Collins said one of his top goals as a member of Congress would be to work with his colleagues to pass a new Farm Bill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpnnow.com/topstories/x1781253499/Collins-talks-to-farmers-in-27th-Congressional-District |title=Collins talks to farmers in 27th Congressional District - News - MPNnow - Canandaigua, NY |publisher=MPNnow |date=2013-01-07 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> On May 15, 2013 Collins voted to approve the 2013 Farm Bill.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://thedailynewsonline.com/news/article_87c058ec-bea2-11e2-9e6c-001a4bcf887a.html |title=Farm Bill sent to full House, Senate - The Daily News Online: News |publisher=The Daily News Online |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://agriculture.house.gov/press-release/house-ag-committee-approves-farm-bill-significant-savings-reforms |title=House Ag Committee Approves Farm Bill With Significant Savings & Reforms &#124; Committee on Agriculture |publisher=Agriculture.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Subsequently, on January 29, 2014 Collins voted to approve the Conferenced Farm Bill, known as the Agricultural Act of 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Sloane|title=Farm Bill Passes House|url=http://www.wbta1490.com/LocalNews/tabid/115/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/4768/Farm-Bill-Passes-House.aspx|accessdate=10 February 2014|newspaper=WBTA AM 1490|date=29 January 2014}}</ref> President Obama signed the 5 year Agricultural Act of 2014 into law on February 7, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shear|first=Michael|title=In Signing Farm Bill, Obama Extols Rural Growth|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/08/us/politics/farm-bill.html?_r=0|accessdate=10 February 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=7 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn June 5, 2013 Collins was asked to join the Committee on Science, Space and Technology. This assignment made Collins the member of three congressional committees, a rarity among members of Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chriscollins.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-collins-adds-third-congressional-committee-assignment-0 |title=Congressman Chris Collins Adds Third Congressional Committee Assignment &#124; Congressman Chris Collins |publisher=Chriscollins.house.gov |date=2013-06-06 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nCollins has been critical of the federal Veterans' Administration since taking office. Collins has said the VA has been unresponsive to several of his concerns and that the agency\u2019s track record is unimpressive. He has called for a top-to-bottom review to address such matters as the massive disability claims backlog and the misuse use of insulin injection pens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capitaltonightny.ynn.com/2013/03/collins-continues-his-assault-on-the-v-a/ |title=Collins Continues his Assault on the V.A |publisher=Capitaltonightny.ynn.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Due to the inappropriate use of single use insulin injection pens at the VA hospital in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], it was reported that 20 veterans tested positive for hepatitis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxrio2.com/80573/health-matters-veterans-tested-positive-for-hepatitis-in-new-york/ |title=Health Matters: Veterans Test Positive For Hepatitis In New York &#124; Fox Rio 2 News RGV |publisher=Foxrio2.com |date=2013-05-10 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> Following this news, Collins called for the resignation of Secretary of Veterans Affairs [[Eric Shinseki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wgrz.com/news/article/213967/292/18-Patients-at-Buffalo-VA-Test-Positive-for-Hepatitis- |title=18 Patients at Buffalo VA Test Positive for Hepatitis |publisher=wgrz.com |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/news/article/379924/28/20-veterans-test-positive-for-hepatits-after-insulin-pens-reused |title=20 veterans test positive for hepatits In Buffalo, N.Y. after insulin pens reused |publisher=ksdk.com |date=2013-05-10 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n\nIn response to a proposal by New York State Governor Andrew Cuomo to provide state prison inmates with a publicly financed college education, Collins introduced the Kids Before Cons Act in February of 2014.<ref>Kasperowicz, Pete (26, February 2014).  \"[http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/government-oversight/199287-should-taxpayers-fund-college-courses-for-inmates Should taxpayers fund college courses for prison inmates]\".  ''The Hill'' </ref>  The bill would prohibit states from using federal funding for the purpose of providing a college degree to convicted criminals.  Collins called the Governor's proposal an insult to law abiding taxpayers who are struggling to put themselves or their children through college.<ref>''The Livingston County News'' (21, February 2014) \"[http://www.thelcn.com/news/collins-joins-state-legislators-in-oppostion-to-cuomo-s-college/article_40c2824a-9ab5-11e3-ac4e-001a4bcf887a.html Collins joins state legislators in opposition to Cuomo's 'College for Convicts' Plan]\"</ref>  Collins' bill does allow federal dollars to be used for GED and working training programs in prisons and correctional facilities.  Cuomo later abandoned his proposal to use public money to fund his initiative.<ref>Kaplan, Thomas (2, April 2014).  \"[http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/03/nyregion/cuomo-drops-plan-to-use-state-money-to-pay-for-college-classes-for-inmates.html?_r=0 Cuomo Drops Plan to Use State Money to Pay for College Classes for Inmates]\"  ''The New York Times''</ref>\n\nOn May 1, 2014, Collins and Congressman Kurt Schrader (D-OR) sent a letter to EPA Administrator Gina McCarthy and Department of the Army Secretary John M. McHugh voicing concerns with a proposed rule to expand the definition of \u2018navigable waters\u2019 under the Clean Water Act. Two hundred and thirty-one (231) House Members co-signed the letter (212 Republican and 19 Democrats) demanding the EPA and Army Corps of Engineers abandon the proposal because of the negative impact it would have on American farms.<ref>{{cite news|last=Turner|first=Douglas|title=EPA\u2019s power-grab is cause for alarm|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/columns/douglas-turner/epas-power-grab-is-cause-for-alarm-20140512|accessdate=12 May 2014|newspaper=The Buffalo News|date=12 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Goad|first=Benjamin|title=200 lawmakers push EPA to rescind water regulation|url=http://thehill.com/regulation/energy-environment/205002-200-lawmakers-push-epa-to-rescind-water-regulation|accessdate=2 May 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=1 May 2014}}</ref> Collins and Schrader's effort was supported by the American Farm Bureau.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture|Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Health and Technology|Subcommittee on Health and Technology]] (Chair)\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations|Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research and Technology|Subcommittee on Research and Technology]]\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n{{col-begin|width=100%}}\n{{col-break|width=40%}}\n*Auto Industry Pension Task Force\n*Automotive Performance and Motorsports Caucus\n*Canada-U.S. Caucus\n*Dairy Farmers Caucus\n*Diabetes Caucus\n*Fire Services Caucus\n*House Manufacturing Caucus\n*International Conservation Caucus\n*Job Creators' Caucus\n*Natural Gas Caucus\n*Pilot Caucus\n* Scouting Caucus, Chairman<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chriscollins.house.gov/legislation/committees-and-caucuses |title=Committees and Caucuses &#124; Congressman Chris Collins |publisher=Chriscollins.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref>\n{{col-break|width=60%}}\n*Small Business Caucus\n*Small Business Information Technology Caucus\n*STEM Education Caucus\n*Toy Caucus\n*House General Aviation Caucus\n*House Republican Israel Caucus\n*Law Enforcement Caucus\n*National Guard and Reserve Components Caucus\n*New York Defense Working Group\n*Northern Border Caucus\n*Republican Study Committee\n*Technology Transfer Caucus\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Controversies==\nIn October 2009, Collins compared [[Sheldon Silver]], the Jewish speaker of the [[New York State Assembly]], with [[Adolf Hitler]], [[Napoleon]] and the [[Antichrist]]. Collins apologized for his comments.<ref>{{cite news |title=Erie County Executive Collins regrets comparing Sheldon Silver to Hitler, anti-Christ |first=Elizabeth |last=Benjamin |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-10-26/news/17935078_1_gubernatorial-bid-governor-and-legislative-leaders-anti |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |date=October 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, a Republican Assemblyman claimed that at a crowded gubernatorial address, Collins told a woman that \"I'm sure if you offer someone a lap dance you can find a place to sit.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Collins Alleged Remark Creates Controversy |first=Aaron |last=Saykin |url=http://www.wgrz.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=73556 |work=[[WGRZ]] |date=January 14, 2010 }}</ref> Collins denied making the statement attributed to him.<ref>{{cite web|last=Geoffery |first=Ginger |url=http://www.wkbw.com/news/local/81370512.html |title=Did Erie Co. Exec. Ask Woman for Lap Dance? &#124; WKBW News 7: News, Sports, Weather &#124; Buffalo, NY &#124; Top Stories |publisher=Wkbw.com |date=2010-07-09 |accessdate=2013-09-05}}</ref> These two controversies were widely seen as the reason he did not run for Governor of New York in 2010.<ref name=defeated/><ref name=ends/>\n\nCollins made national news due to an interview published in ''The Batavian'' on June 24, 2012, in which he said: \"People now don\u2019t die from prostate cancer, breast cancer and some of the other things. The fact of the matter is, our healthcare today is so much better, we\u2019re living so much longer, because of innovations in drug development, surgical procedures, stents, implantable cardiac defibrillators, neural stimulators -- they didn\u2019t exist 10 years ago.\" <ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Collins wants to go to Washington to restore the American Dream |first=Howard |last=Owens |url=http://thebatavian.com/howard-owens/chris-collins-wants-go-washington-restore-american-dream/32549 |newspaper=The Batavian |date=June 24, 2012 |accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref> In response, [[The Huffington Post]] wrote, \"An estimated 577,190 people in the United States will die from cancer this year, including about 39,920 deaths from breast cancer and 28,170 from prostate cancer,\" citing data from the [[American Cancer Society]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Chris Collins: 'People Now Don't Die From Prostate Cancer, Breast Cancer' |first=Elise |last=Foley |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/03/chris-collins-cancer_n_1647196.html |newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=July 3, 2012 |accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref> [[ArtVoice]] wrote, \"The implantable cardiac defibrillator and neural stimulators, or TENS devices, were both invented and patented in the late 60s or early 70s; therefore, they existed '10 years ago'.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.artvoice.com/avdaily/2012/07/03/collins-people-dont-die-from-prostate-breast-cancers-anymore/|title=Collins: People Don\u2019t Die from Prostate, Breast Cancers Anymore|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the national media picked up the story, ''Batavian'' publisher Howard Owens defended Collins: \"On its face, the opening part of the quote from Collins sounds outrageous, but in context, clearly Collins misspoke. More likely, he meant to say: \u2018Fewer people die from prostate cancer, breast cancer and some of the other things.\u2019\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city/politics/article933937.ece|title=Media seize on comment by Collins|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, Collins introduced the Kids before Cons Act, which would prohibit the use of federal money to provide college education to convicted criminals in prison. An editorial in the New York Times said, \"These ridiculous arguments are unmoored from both reason and reality.\" The investment would have paid for itself many times over. A 2013 RAND study of 30 years of research found that every dollar spent on inmate education saves $4 to $5 on re-incarceration.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/09/opinion/gov-cuomo-drops-the-ball.html Gov. Cuomo Drops the Ball], Editorial, New York Times, April 8, 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://chriscollins.house.gov/ Congressman Chris Collins] official U.S. House site\n*[http://collinsforcongress.com/ Chris Collins for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Chris_Collins_%5BR-27%5D|Chris Collins}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = C001092 | ballot = Chris_Collins | nndb = | votesmart = 139770 | govtrack = 412563 | opencong = 412563 | rollcall = 3536 | politifact = | fec = C00520379 | opensecrets = N00001285 | assets = | legistorm = 2902/Rep_Chris_Collins.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = NY/Chris_Collins.htm | congress = chris-collins/2151 | worldcat = nc-collins%20chris | cspan = 94144 | rose = | imdb =  | bloomberg = chris-collins | nyt = | wsj = | w